            <div class="ins_notes">
                <span class="note" id="note-1"><a href="#ref-1">[1]</a> Fragment b of this inscription was among the inscriptions acquired in Athens by Lord Elgin (cf. <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/AIUK41/2"><i>AIUK</i> 4.1, no. 2</a>). Together with five other fragments which have been identified as belonging to the same text, and are still in Athens, it records a decree of the Athenian community of Myrina on Lemnos. Lemnos in the northern Aegean was a traditional Athenian possession (important to the city in relation to the grain supply, cf. <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/RO/26"> RO 26</a>) and Myrina, to the west, was one of two Athenian communities on the island, along with Hephaistia to the east. The decree conveys the gratitude of Myrina to the Athenian Council and Assembly for intervening to secure the status of Myrina as an Athenian possession, an intervention which apparently entailed obtaining a decision of the Roman senate to that effect. Copies of the decree were erected in Myrina and on the Athenian acropolis (45-47). The surviving fragments all belong to the Athenian copy. From time to time during the Hellenistic period Lemnos was detached from Athens, and for a long time scholars associated this decree with the restoration of Lemnos to Athenian control which followed the defeat of the Macedonian Perseus by the Romans in 167 BC. More recently, however, it has come to be recognised from what else is known about persons mentioned in the decree, that it should date rather later than this (ca. 145 BC), and it has been suggested that the context may have been disturbances on the island connected with the revolt of Andriskos, who claimed to be Perseus' son and in 149 BC attempted unsuccessfully to liberate Macedonia from Roman control. The Athenian intervention at Rome perhaps successfully prevented the Romans from incorporating Lemnos into the new Roman province of Macedonia, established in 146 BC following the defeat of Andriskos, confirming instead the island's status as a traditional Athenian possession (Knoepfler [= <i>SEG</i> 68.62]). For further disputes regarding the Athenian community on Lemnos in the time of Augustus, see <a href="/inscription/SEG/47143a" class="highlight"><i>SEG</i> 47.143a</a>-<a href="/inscription/SEG/47143b" class="highlight">b</a>. For more detailed discussion of this inscription see <a class="highlight" href="/papers/aiuk-43a/"><i>AIUK</i> vol. 4.3A (<i>BM, Decrees of Other Bodies</i>), no. 7</a>.</span>
            </div>
            

